<p id="p0055">The characteristics of sorption properties of the material are described by the equations of Langmuir and Freundlich. Static exchange capacity (
 <italic>Q</italic>, mg-eq/g) was calculated by the equation:
 <disp-formula id="fd1">
  <label>(1)</label>
  <math id="M1" altimg="si1.svg" alttext="Equation 1.">
   <mrow>
    <mi>Q</mi>
    <mo linebreak="badbreak">=</mo>
    <mfrac>
     <mrow>
      <mrow>
       <mo stretchy="true">(</mo>
       <mrow>
        <msub>
         <mrow>
          <mi>C</mi>
         </mrow>
         <mrow>
          <mn>0</mn>
         </mrow>
        </msub>
        <mo linebreak="badbreak">−</mo>
        <msub>
         <mrow>
          <mi>C</mi>
         </mrow>
         <mrow>
          <mi>t</mi>
         </mrow>
        </msub>
       </mrow>
       <mo stretchy="true">)</mo>
      </mrow>
      <mi>V</mi>
     </mrow>
     <mrow>
      <mi>m</mi>
     </mrow>
    </mfrac>
    <mo>,</mo>
   </mrow>
  </math>
 </disp-formula>where 
 <italic>С</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>0</italic>
 </sub> and 
 <italic>С</italic>
 <sub>
  <italic>t</italic>
 </sub> are the initial and steady-state concentrations of the metal ions in the solution, mg-eq/l; 
 <italic>V</italic> – the solution volume, l; 
 <italic>m</italic> – the sub-sample of sorbent, g.
</p>
